[node name="TutorialText" type="RichTextLabel" parent="MarginContainer/VBoxContainer/ScrollContainer/MarginContainer" unique_id=1840359719]
layout_mode = 2
size_flags_horizontal = 3
size_flags_vertical = 3
theme_override_colors/default_color = Color(0.93, 0.88, 0.78, 1)
theme_override_font_sizes/normal_font_size = 20
theme_override_font_sizes/bold_font_size = 21
bbcode_enabled = true
text = "[center][b][color=#f0d080]✦  Welcome, Daimyō  ✦[/color][/b][/center]

[center]Japan is in a state of chaos. The shogun's grip over the realm has weakened, and local daimyo now fight for regional control. You are in a fight for survival. Your father has just unexpectedly died, leaving his territory to you as the legitimate heir. However, many challenge your succession and prop up your brother as a rival claimant.[/center]

[center]Fight your brother and local governors to reclaim your father's territory. This succession crisis isn't the only threat — neighboring daimyo sense blood in the water and wish to take advantage of your weakened state. Once you eliminate these imminent threats, you will have a strong foundation to expand and conquer all of Japan and establish a new Shogunate. Master city management, force concentration, and strategic expansion to achieve total domination.[/center]

[center]——————————————————————————————[/center]

[center][b][color=#f0d080]Game State & Objective[/color][/b][/center]

[center]You will start by viewing a map of your province — a network of cities connected by roads. Both you and the enemy control a city; all others are neutral and defended by preset garrisons. Defend your territory, defeat the enemy Daimyō, and conquer the entire province by capturing every city![/center]

[center]——————————————————————————————[/center]

[center][b][color=#f0d080]🏯 Cities 🏯[/color][/b][/center]

[center]Cities are the lifeblood of your domain. Each city produces gold and troops every cycle. Troops can be used to defend or capture cities. Gold can be used to upgrade your controlled cities in the following ways:[/center]

							• [b]Gold Production:[/b] Increase gold earned per cycle
							• [b]Unit Production:[/b] Increase troops trained per cycle
							• [b]Improve Defenses:[/b] Strengthen the garrison's defensive bonus

[center][b]Upgrades:[/b] Invest in production and gold in safe interior cities and harden the defenses of exposed frontier cities. Upgrade costs scale steeply, so spread your investments wisely.[/center]

[center][i]How to Upgrade: Hover the cursor over a city, left-click to select it, then select an upgrade in the side panel.[/i][/center]

[center]——————————————————————————————[/center]

[center][b][color=#f0d080]Units[/color][/b][/center]

[center]Units are the soldiers that garrison your cities and march to war. Select a percentage of the troops from a friendly city and drag to an adjacent city to send them. They can reinforce allied cities or storm enemy positions. A city may only send one march at a time.[/center]

[center][b]Troop Concentration:[/b] Combat effectiveness improves when you outnumber the enemy, so always make sure to position your units to outnumber the enemy at any particular encounter. A wise Daimyō never finds themself fighting a disadvantageous battle.[/center]

[center][i]How to Send Troops: Select a city, set the send ratio with the slider, then drag to the destination city.[/i][/center]

[center]——————————————————————————————[/center]

[center][b][color=#f0d080]Combat[/color][/b][/center]

[center]Combat occurs in three scenarios:[/center]

						• [b]Garrison Defense:[/b] An enemy army reaches one of your cities
						• [b]Field Battle:[/b] Two opposing armies meet on a road and lock into battle
						• [b]Siege Attack:[/b] Your army reaches an enemy city

[center][b]Garrisons Battles:[/b] Garrisons provide a defensive bonus depending on the city's defense level, so you will need greater numbers to take a fortified position. When a garrison falls, the victors occupy the city and it begins producing for them. Cities under siege do not produce units, so sending out probes to disrupt enemy production could prove useful.[/center]

[center][b]Field Battles:[/b] Sending a sortie against an enemy army on the road can weaken it and buy time for reinforcements. Split-second decisions on the march can turn the tide of war.[/center]"
fit_content = true

